        "tags": "buddhism ebts buddha function sn sutta philosophy",
        "category": "canon",
        "subcategory": null,
        "boost": 1.6,
        "authors": ["Joseph Goldstein"],
        "translator": "Bhikkhu Bodhi",
        "content": "Who was the Buddha in his own words? In this story, he calls himself the “Tathagata” or “Truth-Arriver”, and he responds to a question on what will become of him after his death. The Buddha explains that he doesn’t talk in such terms, as he has overcome all such notions as “I am the body” or “I am the mind” so how could such a question ever be answered? He ends the discourse by famously saying that all he teaches is suffering and the end of suffering, thus redirecting our attention from empty philosophical musings to the things that matter most.",
